---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout title="Skjera — Tuva Ødegård" lang="en">
  <article>
    <header class="project-header">
      <div class="meta">
        <span class="year">2025</span>
        <span class="badge">Case study</span>
      </div>
      <h1>Skjera</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        An internal platform for sending event invitations — designed from
        initial sketches to a product that's actively in use.
      </p>
      <ul class="tags">
        <li>UX Design</li>
        <li>Design-to-dev</li>
        <li>Design system</li>
        <li>Internal tooling</li>
      </ul>
    </header>

    <div class="content">
      <section>
        <h2>Background</h2>
        <p>
          Event invitations at work were sent through Outlook, Teams, or Slack.
          The tools work, but not everyone has access across the organisation,
          and there was no easy way to get a clear picture of who was actually
          coming. Skjera was a side project
          (built during dedicated learning time) to fix exactly that.
        </p>
        <p>
          I joined from the start and took on the design work. At the time I
          was working on the design system team, so this was also a chance to
          use our own system in a real product — which turned out to be a
          useful way to find its rough edges.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Process</h2>
        <p>
          I started with rough sketches in Figma to establish the core flow:
          an overview page, an event detail page, and a creation form. The
          sketches weren't treated as a final handoff — I stayed close to the
          developers throughout implementation, adjusting designs when we hit
          technical constraints or found that something worked differently in
          practice than it looked on the page.
        </p>
        <p>
          Working together from day one meant we agreed quickly on what to
          prioritise for the first version, and avoided large surprises late
          in the process.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>The solution</h2>
        <p>
          The overview lets you see all events across the organisation, or
          filter down to your own. Each event has a dedicated page with
          description, location, time, and a sign-up button. Once registered,
          you can see who else is coming.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}images/skjera/event_list.png`}
            alt="Overview page showing a list of upcoming events with tags and registration status"
          />
          <figcaption>Figma design: Overview with "My events" and "All events" toggle</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}images/skjera/event_detail_registered.png`}
            alt="Event detail page after registering, showing attendee count and avatar stack"
          />
          <figcaption>Figma design: Event detail after registering — with attendee count and avatar stack</figcaption>
        </figure>
        <p>
          Organisers can create events through a simple form with support for
          categories and an optional attendee cap. After the event, the
          attendee list can be exported — handy for attaching to expense
          reimbursements.
        </p>
        <figure>
          <img
            src={`${import.meta.env.BASE_URL}images/skjera/new_event_form.png`}
            alt="Event creation form with fields for title, location, time, description, and categories"
          />
          <figcaption>Figma design: Creation form built with design system components</figcaption>
        </figure>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Outcome</h2>
        <p>
          The platform is actively used and has made organising internal events
          noticeably easier. Skjera is still a living side project — a user
          profile with dietary preferences is already built, so people don't
          have to answer the same question at every event that involves food.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Design system takeaways</h2>
        <p>
          Using our own design system in a real product surface things that
          abstract testing doesn't. One of the more interesting observations
          wasn't technical: when something was off or missing, people tended
          to just work around it themselves rather than report it. That kind
          of silent workaround is easy to miss if you're only looking at
          adoption numbers — it was a useful reminder that friction in a
          design system doesn't always show up as complaints.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>
  </article>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  article {
    max-width: 680px;
  }

  .project-header {
    margin-bottom: 4rem;
    padding-bottom: 2.5rem;
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--border);
  }

  .meta {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    gap: 0.75rem;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
  }

  .year {
    font-size: 0.85rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
  }

  .badge {
    font-size: 0.7rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    letter-spacing: 0.05em;
    text-transform: uppercase;
    color: var(--accent);
    border: 1px solid var(--accent);
    padding: 0.15rem 0.5rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  h1 {
    font-size: 2rem;
    font-weight: 400;
    margin-bottom: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.2;
  }

  .lead {
    font-size: 1rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    line-height: 1.7;
    margin-bottom: 1.25rem;
  }

  .tags {
    display: flex;
    flex-wrap: wrap;
    gap: 0.4rem;
    list-style: none;
  }

  .tags li {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    background: #ede9e2;
    padding: 0.2rem 0.6rem;
    border-radius: 2px;
  }

  .content {
    line-height: 1.8;
  }

  .content section {
    margin-bottom: 3rem;
  }

  .content h2 {
    font-size: 0.75rem;
    font-weight: 500;
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    text-transform: uppercase;
    letter-spacing: 0.06em;
  }

  .content p {
    margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
    color: var(--text);
  }

  .content p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  .content figure {
    margin: 1.5rem 0;
  }

  .content figure img {
    width: 100%;
    border-radius: 4px;
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    display: block;
  }

  .content figure figcaption {
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    margin-top: 0.5rem;
  }
</style>
